{"title_page": "Elena Semino", "text_new": "{{short description|British linguist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Elena Semino\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = \n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1969|9|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Genoa]], [[Italy]]\n| residence         = [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| fields =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[Stylistics]]\n* [[Critical discourse analysis]]\n  }}\n| workplaces =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[Lancaster University]]\n\n  }}\n| alma_mater =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[University of Genoa]]\n* [[Lancaster University]]\n  }}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| thesis_title = \n| thesis_url =\n| thesis_year = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students =\n| known_for =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[Critical discourse analysis]]\n\n  }}\n| author_abbrev_bot =\n| author_abbrev_zoo =\n| awards =\n  {{plainlist | style = white-space: nowrap; |\n\n  }}\n| spouse = Jonathan Culpeper\n  {{plainlist |\n}}\n| children = \n  {{plainlist |\n}}\n| religion = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/linguistics/about-us/people/elena-semino|Semino on the website of Lancaster University}}\n}}\n\n'''Elena Semino''' (born 9 September 1964) is an [[Italian people|Italian]]-born [[British people|British]] [[linguist]] whose research involves stylistics and [[metaphor]] [[theory]]. Focusing on [[figurative language]] in a range of poetic and prose works, most recently she has worked on topics from the domains of medical humanities and health communication. Her projects use [[Corpus linguistics|corpus linguistic]] methods as well as [[qualitative research|qualitative analysis]].\n\nShe served as Head of the Department of Linguistics and English Language at [[Lancaster University]] from 2013 to 2019.\n\n== Biography ==\nSemino earned her BA in 1988 in Foreign Languages and Literature from the [[University of Genoa]], Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.via-academy.org/VIA/index.php?title=Elena_Semino|title=Elena Semino|work=via-academy.org|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> She received her MA in 1990 and her PhD in 1994 from [[Lancaster University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ethos.bl.uk/SearchResults.do|title=British Library EThOS - Search and order theses online|work=bl.uk|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref>  She taught Italian as a foreign language at [[Napier Polytechnic]] (Edinburgh) and at Lancaster University, where in 1992 she took a position as lecturer in the Department of Linguistics and English Language. She became a senior Senior Lecturer in Linguistics there in 2003. She is currently a Professor of Linguistics and Verbal Art and served as Head of the Department of Linguistics and English Language between 2013 and 2019.\n\nShe serves on the editorial board of ''Critical Approaches to Discourse Analysis Across Disciplines'' and ''Metaphor and the Social World''.<ref>https://www.benjamins.com/#catalog/journals/msw/board</ref>\n\nSemino has been a co-PI on grants from the UK's Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC) and the Brazilian research agency CONFAP to study the linguistic representation of urban violence in Brazil using [[corpus linguistics]] methods,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cass.lancs.ac.uk/?author=6|title=Elena Semino - ESRC Centre for Corpus Approaches to Social Science (CASS)|work=lancs.ac.uk|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> and a project to funded by ESRC that details how metaphors are used in end-of-life care in the UK (MELC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ucrel.lancs.ac.uk/melc/index.php|title=Metaphor in end of life care (MELC). project|work=lancs.ac.uk|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 November 2018, Semino said that the academics at the [[University of Mosul]] are \"working in conditions that we cannot even imagine\" after the Department of Linguistics and English Language at Lancaster University facilitated to support the teaching of linguistics at [[Mosul]], [[Iraq]], providing mentoring for staff and students via video-conferencing, advice for PhD students and free access to an online course.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iraqi university rebuilds after IS 'dark age'\n|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-46208714|publisher=BBC.com|language=English|date=21 November 2018|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*E. Semino. ''Metaphor in discourse.'' Cambridge University Press. 2008<ref>{{cite book | last=Semino | first=Elena | title=Metaphor in discourse | publisher=Cambridge University Press | location=Cambridge, UK New York | year=2008 | isbn=0-521-68696-2 | language=nl | ref=harv}}</ref>\n*E. Semino and M. Short. ''Corpus stylistics: Speech, writing and thought presentation in a corpus of English writing''. Routledge. 2004<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Corpus-Stylistics-Presentation-Routledge-Linguistics/dp/1138008621|title=Amazon.com: Corpus Stylistics: Speech, Writing and Thought Presentation in a Corpus of English Writing (Routledge Advances in Corpus Linguistics) (9781138008625): Elena Semino, Mick Short: Books|work=amazon.com|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref>\n*E. Semino, J. Heywood, M. Short. Methodological problems in the analysis of metaphors in a corpus of conversations about cancer. ''Journal of Pragmatics.'' 2004<ref>{{cite book | last=Wan | first=W. | last2=Low | first2=G. | title=Elicited Metaphor Analysis in Educational Discourse | publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company | series=Metaphor in Language, Cognition, and Communication | year=2015 | isbn=978-90-272-6843-3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jPEZCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA92 | ref=harv | accessdate=2015-11-16}}</ref>\n*E. Seminno and J. Culpeper. ''Cognitive stylistics: Language and cognition in text analysis.'' John Benjamins. 2002<ref>{{cite book | last=Semino | first=E. | last2=Culpeper | first2=J. | title=Cognitive Stylistics: Language and Cognition in Text Analysis | publisher=J. Benjamins Publishing Company | series=Linguistic approaches to literature | year=2002 | isbn=978-90-272-3331-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O1R79-TsVKoC | ref=harv | accessdate=2015-11-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n\u2022 [http://www.ling.lancs.ac.uk/profiles/elena-semino  Faculty web page at Lancaster]\n\n\u2022 {{twitter|elenasemino}}\n\n\u2022 [http://scienceblog.cancerresearchuk.org/2015/09/28/may-i-take-your-metaphor-how-we-talk-about-cancer/2015 Video: May I take your metaphor? \u2013 how we talk about cancer. Cancer Research UK]\n\n\u2022 [https://www.facebook.com/660517607312711/videos/759901724040965/  2014 Video: Discussion of a character with autistic spectrum disorder of 'The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time. Stylistics]\n\n{{Critical discourse analysis}}\n{{Department of Linguistics and English Language, Lancaster University}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Semino, Elena}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Linguists from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Women linguists]]\n[[Category:British women writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Lancaster University]]\n[[Category:University of Genoa alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Academics of Lancaster University]]\n[[Category:Italian emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:Department of Linguistics and English Language, Lancaster University]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British linguist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Elena Semino\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = \n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1969|9|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Genoa]], [[Italy]]\n| residence         = [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| fields =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[Stylistics]]\n* [[Critical discourse analysis]]\n  }}\n| workplaces =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[Lancaster University]]\n\n  }}\n| alma_mater =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[University of Genoa]]\n* [[Lancaster University]]\n  }}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| thesis_title = \n| thesis_url =\n| thesis_year = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students =\n| known_for =\n  {{plainlist |\n* [[Critical discourse analysis]]\n\n  }}\n| author_abbrev_bot =\n| author_abbrev_zoo =\n| awards =\n  {{plainlist | style = white-space: nowrap; |\n\n  }}\n| spouse = Jonathan Culpeper\n  {{plainlist |\n}}\n| children = \n  {{plainlist |\n}}\n| religion = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/linguistics/about-us/people/elena-semino|Semino on the website of Lancaster University}}\n}}\n\n'''Elena Semino''' (born 9 September 1964) is an [[Italian people|Italian]]-born [[British people|British]] [[linguist]] whose research involves stylistics and [[metaphor]] [[theory]]. Focusing on [[figurative language]] in a range of poetic and prose works, most recently she has worked on topics from the domains of medical humanities and health communication. Her projects use [[Corpus linguistics|corpus linguistic]] methods as well as [[qualitative research|qualitative analysis]].\n\nShe served as Head of the Department of Linguistics and English Language at [[Lancaster University]] from 2013 to 2019.\n\n== Biography ==\nSemino earned her BA in 1988 in Foreign Languages and Literature from the [[University of Genoa]], Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.via-academy.org/VIA/index.php?title=Elena_Semino|title=Elena Semino|work=via-academy.org|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> She received her MA in 1990 and her PhD in 1994 from [[Lancaster University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ethos.bl.uk/SearchResults.do|title=British Library EThOS - Search and order theses online|work=bl.uk|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref>  She taught Italian as a foreign language at [[Napier Polytechnic]] (Edinburgh) and at Lancaster University, where in 1992 she took a position as lecturer in the Department of Linguistics and English Language. She became a senior Senior Lecturer in Linguistics there in 2003. She is currently a Professor of Linguistics and Verbal Art and served as Head of the Department of Linguistics and English Language between 2013 and 2019.\n\nShe serves on the editorial board of ''Critical Approaches to Discourse Analysis Across Disciplines'' and ''Metaphor and the Social World''.<ref>https://www.benjamins.com/#catalog/journals/msw/board</ref>\n\nSemino has been a co-PI on grants from the UK's Economic and Social Research Council (ESRC) and the Brazilian research agency CONFAP to study the linguistic representation of urban violence in Brazil using [[corpus linguistics]] methods,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cass.lancs.ac.uk/?author=6|title=Elena Semino - ESRC Centre for Corpus Approaches to Social Science (CASS)|work=lancs.ac.uk|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> and a project to funded by ESRC that details how metaphors are used in end-of-life care in the UK (MELC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ucrel.lancs.ac.uk/melc/index.php|title=Metaphor in end of life care (MELC). project|work=lancs.ac.uk|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 November 2018, Semino said that the academics at the [[University of Mosul]] are \"working in conditions that we cannot even imagine\" after the Department of Linguistics and English Language at Lancaster University facilitated to support the teaching of linguistics at [[Mosul]], [[Iraq]], providing mentoring for staff and students via video-conferencing, advice for PhD students and free access to an online course.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iraqi university rebuilds after IS 'dark age'\n|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-46208714|publisher=BBC.com|language=English|date=21 November 2018|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*E. Semino. ''Metaphor in discourse.'' Cambridge University Press. 2008<ref>{{cite book | last=Semino | first=Elena | title=Metaphor in discourse | publisher=Cambridge University Press | location=Cambridge, UK New York | year=2008 | isbn=0-521-68696-2 | language=nl | ref=harv}}</ref>\n*E. Semino and M. Short. ''Corpus stylistics: Speech, writing and thought presentation in a corpus of English writing''. Routledge. 2004<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Corpus-Stylistics-Presentation-Routledge-Linguistics/dp/1138008621|title=Amazon.com: Corpus Stylistics: Speech, Writing and Thought Presentation in a Corpus of English Writing (Routledge Advances in Corpus Linguistics) (9781138008625): Elena Semino, Mick Short: Books|work=amazon.com|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref>\n*E. Semino, J. Heywood, M. Short. Methodological problems in the analysis of metaphors in a corpus of conversations about cancer. ''Journal of Pragmatics.'' 2004<ref>{{cite book | last=Wan | first=W. | last2=Low | first2=G. | title=Elicited Metaphor Analysis in Educational Discourse | publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company | series=Metaphor in Language, Cognition, and Communication | year=2015 | isbn=978-90-272-6843-3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jPEZCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA92 | ref=harv | accessdate=2015-11-16}}</ref>\n*E. Seminno and J. Culpeper. ''Cognitive stylistics: Language and cognition in text analysis.'' John Benjamins. 2002<ref>{{cite book | last=Semino | first=E. | last2=Culpeper | first2=J. | title=Cognitive Stylistics: Language and Cognition in Text Analysis | publisher=J. Benjamins Publishing Company | series=Linguistic approaches to literature | year=2002 | isbn=978-90-272-3331-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O1R79-TsVKoC | ref=harv | accessdate=2015-11-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External sources==\n\u2022 [http://www.ling.lancs.ac.uk/profiles/elena-semino  Faculty web page at Lancaster]\n\n\u2022 [https://twitter.com/elenasemino Twitter profile]\n\n\u2022 [http:/